post_text:
Mrs. Nola Manis
May 12 1959 -August 16 2020
22 years with Carthage ISD

While our school is mourning the loss of an exceptional teacher and person, our students are mourning the loss of a person no less than their mother. The death of Mrs. Nola Manis has had a sad impact upon administrators, faculty members, staff, students, and the school as a whole. She was of the Baptist faith and served in the ministry with her husband Jerry for 39 years. She enjoyed spending time with her grandchildren, being a school teacher for over twenty-eight years, watching movies, influencing and touching people’s lives. Nola was caring, compassionate, thoughtful and loving.

Goodbye is the hardest thing to say to someone who meant the world to us, especially when goodbye isn’t what we want to say.
Mrs. Manis, we will miss you.

"Trust in the Lord with all your heart; do not depend on your own understanding. Seek his will in all you do, and he will show you which path to take."
—Proverbs 3:5–6
shared_text:
Carthage High School
August 17 at 9:13 AM ·

Yesterday evening we lost a true warrior for Christ, beloved friend, teacher and Carthage ISD great, Nola Manis. Mrs. Manis has mentored many students as well as staff members during her time in Carthage ISD. She was known most for her loving spirit, her kind nature and uncanny ability to help students understand science. It is with a heavy heart this morning that we share this news of such a great loss to our school, community and body of believers. Details of arrangements and celebration of life will come in the following days. In the mean time, please pray for the bereaved family.

My deepest condolences to her many friends, colleagues, and family members.

Justin Smith
CHS Principal

post_text:
Bulldogs, let’s welcome Lindsey Byrd to the Baker•Koonce Intermediate School family! Mrs. Byrd is a new teacher to our district this year and will teach fourth grade math.

“I was born and raised in Carthage, now all three of my children are attending CISD schools,” Mrs. Byrd shared. “We love being Bulldogs! It’s such a wonderful school district and I can’t wait to continue being involved in the place I call home. My grandmother and mother were involved in different aspects of education within CISD, so I was practically raised in the hallways of Primary and Baker Koonce. I knew from a young age that it’s what I wanted to do. I have a passion for helping children learn new concepts and there’s absolutely nothing better than seeing that lightbulb go off when they finally understand something they’ve struggled with.”

Fun facts: Mrs. Byrd and her mother, Julie White, are both SFA graduates and will both be teaching at Baker Koonce this year.

Welcome to Carthage Mrs. Byrd!

Bulldogs, let’s welcome Adine Mañón to the Carthage High School family! Mrs. Mañón is a new teacher to our district this year and will be the Lifeskills teacher. She’s coming to Carthage from Kilgore ISD.

“I am excited to be a part of a district that is very welcoming, encouraging, and cares about its students and providing the best education possible,” Mrs. Mañón shared. “I had teachers that made a lasting impact in my life throughout my education and I want to be able to do the same, serve others, and make a difference in my students' lives. I also learn from my students and I am blessed through this experience.”

Fun facts: Mrs. Mañón has a 6 year old son, Hayden, who is her pride and joy. She is a proud SFA alumni.

Welcome to Carthage Mrs. Mañón!

Bulldogs, let’s welcome Emily Roberson to the Carthage High School family! Ms. Roberson is a new teacher to our district this year and will be the Bulldog Belles Director. She’s coming to Carthage from Cumberland ISD- Leadership Academy and has three years of experience as a dance instructor.

“I’m excited to be back at my alma mater and to carry on the drill team program that I helped establish in 2013,” Ms. Roberson shared. “Teaching has always been natural to me, especially dance. I hope to use my passion for dance and education to allow my students to learn what their passions are in life and help them become successful humans in the world.”

Fun facts: In her free time, she enjoys golfing and traveling!

Welcome to Carthage Ms. Roberson!

post_text:
Bulldogs, let’s welcome Kaylie Andrews to the Carthage Junior High School family! Mrs. Andrews is a new teacher to our district this year and will teach eighth grade science. She has been a stay at home mom for the last several years, but previously taught at Beckville High School and has three years of experience in teaching.

“I have always been a bulldog at heart,” Mrs. Andrews shared. “I graduated from Carthage ten years ago and I am so excited to be coming home, as a not only an alumni, but a part of the CISD family. My family has always joked that teaching is just in our blood. My mother and grandmother were great inspirations, and I grew up hearing classroom stories and all about the life of a teacher. So, when the Lord opened the door for me to begin teaching, I followed. I love teaching kids new things, and I have no doubt that this is what I am meant to be doing.”

Fun facts: She has been married to her husband, Russell, for three years and they have a two year old daughter, Bristell.

Welcome to Carthage Mrs. Andrews!

Bulldogs, let’s welcome Angela Webster to the Carthage High School family! Mrs. Webster is a new teacher to our district this year and will teach Spanish 1 and 2. She’s coming back to Carthage after having taught here from 1999 through 2014 and has over twenty years of experience.

“I’m thrilled to be back at CHS with the rest of the amazing Bulldog Nation,” Mrs. Webster shared. “Being a teenager is a very difficult time of life. I wanted to become a teacher and be someone that would help students grow to reach their full potential. At the same time, I want to provide an environment where students are learning they are loved and have value beyond measure.”

Fun facts: She’s been known to eat some very strange things in her lifetime. If you ask, she might tell you!

Welcome back to Carthage Mrs. Webster!

“The saying is ‘Once a Bulldog, always a Bulldog” and how true that is,” Mrs. Cole shared. “I am beyond excited to join Carthage Primary! I have always had a passion about helping children in need. I knew I wanted a career that had to do with helping children; I just had to make the decision between nursing and teaching. Being an elementary teacher is very rewarding and I love every minute of it!”

Fun facts: Mrs. Cole is married to Dustin and they have 2 children: Adaline and Luke.

Bulldogs, let’s welcome Kendrick Haskins to the Carthage High School family! Mr. Haskins is a new teacher to our district this year and will be a Special Education teacher. He’s coming to Carthage from Life School Oak Cliff and has four years of experience in teaching.

“Becoming a Bulldog puts me back in East Texas where I was born and raised,” Mr. Haskins shared. “I’m back in a small community where everyone loves and supports the school! That is very important to me! I wanted to become a teacher so that I can give back to my community by being a positive role model to our youth. I may not be able to reach EVERY student, but if I can change one life, then that’s a win.”

Fun facts: Mr. Haskins graduated high school at Linden-Kildare CISD. He graduated college from The University of North Texas and served 10 years in the United States Air Force. He served two combat tours in 9 total countries. He is also a member of Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity Inc.

Thank you for your service to our country Mr. Haskins and welcome to Carthage!

Bulldogs, let’s welcome Catherine Jackson to the Carthage High School family! Mrs. Jackson is a new teacher to our district this year and will be teaching in the English department. She will also be the National Honor Society sponsor and UIL Ready Writing coach. She’s coming to Carthage from the Galveston area and has over twenty years of experience in teaching.

“The community feeling and 'togetherness' that I experienced when visiting the campus is probably the most exciting thing for me,” Mrs. Jackson shared. “I love that the district puts students first and really cares about each one. It is inspiring to see a district invested 100% in their students. I grew up in a low income family household where my mom had to work 2 to 3 jobs consistently just to survive, and I was fortunate to have had some amazing teachers that changed my life and taught me that I am always more than my circumstance. This inspired me. A teacher changed my life, and now I strive to do the same thing.”

Welcome to Carthage Mrs. Jackson!

post_text:
Our faculty members at CISD are hard at work this summer to continue striving for excellence in the upcoming year!

Kim Horton is an English Language Arts teacher at Carthage High School and has been with the district for twenty-three years. This summer Mrs. Horton has attended training for a new textbook the high school is adopting, Study Sync training and Google certification.

“I chose these trainings so that I can attempt to utilize all of the tools out there to improve the education I provide for all types of learners,” Mrs. Horton shared. “Our electronic textbooks are interactive and engaging. The most important thing I’ve learned is how to switch to ‘At Home Learning’ without sacrificing rigor. To me, electronics can’t replace me as the teacher, but I have learned how to make the experience more effective for my students”

These training sessions and professional development are an asset to our faculty and ultimately benefit our students in a number of ways.

Thank you Mrs. Horton for your hard work this summer and for all you do for our students!

Our faculty members at CISD are hard at work this summer to continue striving for excellence in the upcoming year!

Natalie Brewster is a Math and Science teacher at Libby Elementary School and has been with the district for fifteen years. This summer Mrs. Brewster has attended webinars through Region 7 covering Google Basics, Youtube for Teachers, Zoom for teachers, and more!

“I chose these trainings because I want to be properly prepared to assist any student with online learning, if it comes to that,” Mrs. Brewster shared. “Thanks to these training sessions, I’ll be able to successfully manage my Google Classroom. All of these webinars are preparing me to be the best online teacher I can be. To be that teacher, I have to have an idea of how to navigate the tools our district has provided.”

These training sessions and professional development are an asset to our faculty and ultimately benefit our students in a number of ways.

Thank you Mrs. Brewster for your hard work this summer and for all you do for our students!

post_text:
Our faculty members at CISD are hard at work this summer to continue striving for excellence in the upcoming year!

Sherry Parker is the Government and Economics teacher at Carthage High School and has been with the district for seven years. Mrs. Parker attended advanced Google Training to attain Level 2 Google certification this summer.

“Going remote after spring break taught me that I needed to improve the quality of my online curriculum to better reach my students,” Mrs. Parker shared. “This summer I have built my Google site to host all of my coursework, created multiple virtual classrooms, and have recorded several of my Government lectures. I’ve also been reading my book for our upcoming UIL Social Studies competition and preparing for those contests.”

These training sessions and professional development are an asset to our faculty and ultimately benefit our students in a number of ways.

Thank you Mrs. Parker for your hard work this summer and for all you do for our students!

“Kahoot! is a useful tool for both in class and online teaching,” Mrs. Reyes shared. “We can Kahoot! with other classes simultaneously, make flashcards and more! There are now certification levels for Kahoot also and teachers can become Kahoot! certified. This will be invaluable to me next year and will be a fun new thing to incorporate.”

These training sessions and professional development are an asset to our faculty and ultimately benefit our students in a number of ways.

Thank you Mrs. Reyes for your hard work this summer and for all you do for our students!

Our faculty members at CISD are hard at work this summer to continue striving for excellence in the upcoming year!

Sherrie Russell is an Early Childhood Special Education teacher at Carthage Primary and has been with the district for sixteen years. Mrs. Russell has been completing courses and training in order to obtain her Master’s degree of Education in School Counseling.

“I want to help students overcome their challenges and achieve growth in their academic and personal lives,” Mrs. Russell said. “During the upcoming school year I want to explore the emotions and feelings that cause certain behaviors in the classroom and help our students be able to cope and adapt.”

These training sessions and professional development are an asset to our faculty and ultimately benefit our students in a number of ways.

Thank you Mrs. Russell for your hard work this summer and for all you do for our students!

Our faculty members at CISD are hard at work this summer to continue striving for excellence in the upcoming year!

Kim Funderburk is the Theatre teacher at Carthage High School and has been with our district for twenty-five years. This summer she's virtually attending the UIL Capital Conference, Theatre workshops for Region 7, Google Training and intensive planning for the CHS Student Council, UIL Academic Team and Theatre Department.

“The UIL Capital Conference will help me be knowledgeable of the UIL rule changes and will help me improve the performance of the students at CHS in a wide variety of UIL events,” said Mrs. Funderburk. “I’m excited to bring new scripts and new lessons to my students next year!”

These training sessions and professional development are an asset to our teachers and ultimately benefit our students in a number of ways.

Thank you Mrs. Funderburk for your hard work this summer and for all you do for our students!

Our faculty members at CISD are hard at work this summer to continue striving for excellence in the upcoming year!

Linda Kimberly is a Math Intervention and ESL teacher at Carthage Junior High School and has been a Bulldog for nine years! This summer she’s attending a 2020 Curriculum Extravaganza, training for Pear Deck, Google Classroom and Math that Stick, and in-house departmental planning.

“Pear Deck is amazing and allows you to create some very nice guided lessons for the entire classroom,” shared Mrs. Kimberly. “You can control the speed of delivery, ensure that everyone is on the same page, and view options for assessment as you go. It’s going to be a real help in Math Intervention to be able to get real-time checks for understanding.”

These training sessions and professional development are an asset to our teachers and ultimately benefit our students in a number of ways.

Thank you Mrs. Kimberly for your dedication this summer and for all you do for our students!

CJHS Summer School Information:

SUMMER SCHOOL!

Summer School for currently enrolled 7th Graders will be offered at CJHS June 29-July 30, Monday-Thursday mornings 8:00 am-12:00 noon. Transportation is available plus free breakfast and free lunch. Please contact the junior high for more information. 903-693-2751.

Eighth graders interested in summer school should contact Carthage High School, 903-693-2552.

post_text: We are pleased to welcome Justin Smith as the new principal at Carthage High School. He comes to us from Bryan ISD and brings a wealth of knowledge and compassion for students. He will be an asset to our faculty, students and community. Please join us in welcoming him to Carthage.

post_text:
Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.
P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT
text:
Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.
P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

post_text: Thank you Ms. Murray for your dedication to CISD! Happy Retirement!
shared_text:
Carthage Junior High School
May 8 at 7:20 AM ·

This morning CJHS would like to celebrate Shirley Murray and congratulate her on a fantastic career. Shirley gave 39 years to CISD and the children of Carthage. There are not enough words to describe the impact she has made on both students and faculty. We will miss her knowledge, expertise and experience. Most of all we will be missing what we all consider a dear friend. We wish Shirley the best in her next chapter of her life with her kids and grandkids in Alabama. Our loss, is their gain!

I’ve been married to my husband for 10 years and we have 3 beautiful kids. Demi is almost 8, Dax is 5 and Dane is 2. We enjoy spending time together, watching Demi play softball with her travel team and being outdoors!

shared_text:
City of Carthage, Texas - City Hall
March 9 at 11:47 AM ·

Thanks to the welding classes of Ms. Jolene Davis at Carthage High School and the beautiful stone work of Curt Crawford, we have a new sign adorning the entrance to Davis Park.

The "Davis Park" letters and scroll work are part of the original sign to the park entrance on N. St. Mary Street that was torn down by a truck last year. Davis' students took on the project of reworking the metal and bringing it back to new. Crawford installed the sign and added the stonework. We think it's GORGEOUS!

The students in Ms. Davis' Welding I class are Robert Andrews, Bryce Boniol, JJ Brown, Zack Carlisle, Mason Elliot, Coleman Ivy, Caleb King, Christian Lewis, Kolton Marshall, Johnathan Medrano, Patrick Owen, Si Schumacher, Kaed Staton, Lance Cargill, Bobby Cooks, Devin Festervan, Jermaine Johnson, TJ Johnson, Jay Martinez, Chad Rogers, Tristian Rowley, Ralph Whipple, Mitchell Williams, and not pictured - Zay Woods, DK Pellum. Feel free to tag yourself!

post_text: Carthage ISD celebrates Black History Month by recognizing Mrs. Edith Williams Shepherd. Mrs. Shepherd graduated from Turner High School's Class of 1958 as Valedictorian. Upon graduation, she entered Prairie View A&M College and earned her Bachelor of Science Degree in Home Economics. In 1968, she was hired by Carthage ISD as a Home Economics teacher where she remained for 44 years giving her a total of 50 years in the field of education. She dedicated her life to teaching young people in the Carthage Independent School District. It should also be noted that Shepherd pursued and received a Master of Science Degree in Home Economy from Stephen F. Austin State University where she was the first African-American educator to attain such a goal.

post_text: Carthage ISD celebrates Black History Month by recognizing Mr. Hermon Reed, Jr. Mr. Reed was an outstanding educator who began his career in 1960 teaching mathematics, chemistry, and physics at Turner High School. He was responsible for introducing the very first Science Fair at Turner High. After integration, he continued teaching science courses at Carthage Junior and High School until he retired in 1997 after 37 years of teaching. Mr. Reed also served the community in leadership positions including: Board of Trustees at Panola College from 1992 to 2000 and three terms as Panola County Commissioner of Precinct #3 from 2000 to 2012.

post_text: Carthage ISD celebrates Black History Month by recognizing Mrs. Glendell Pope Chadwick. Mrs. Chadwick was a 1967 graduate of Turner High School and served in the education profession for 35 years. She retired as an Educational Diagnostician from the Carthage Independent School District serving students students from CISD as well as those attending the Beckville and Gary Independent School Districts. Mrs. Chadwick was also the owner of the Knowledge Nook Daycare and instrumental in helping children to be academically ready for public school for more than 20 years. She was elected to the Panola College Board of Trustees in 2001 and served until she went to be with her Lord and Savior in 2017.

Carthage High School
February 5 at 3:46 PM ·

The Youth Art Month Top 100 Artists for the Texas Capitol Exhibit has been released. Senior Taylor Kenderdine has earned the honor of All-State Artist three years in a row!

TAEA does not create divisions of 1A-6A. This contest is the Top 100 of K-12 work and all size Districts of both Private and Public Schools in Texas. Her work will be on display at both the Bob Bullock Museum and the State Capitol. A reception will be held March 22 in honor of these amazing artists.

Congratulations Taylor! Your talent continues to amaze us.

(The second picture is this year’s artwork. The third and fourth pictures are her All-State award winning pieces from the previous years.)

BUS WRECK
A CISD bus was hit this afternoon on US Hwy 79E near the Bethlehem Baptist Church. There were no injuries to anyone on the bus, and all students were safely transported home. Investigators need information on a silver 4X4 truck that hit the bus. Please contact Carthage PD if you have information.

🚨 **Excellence Alert** 🚨
Today the CHS Band Auxiliary Flag Line and Twirlers competed in The Vicki Bowden Mobbs Majorette Classic at Kilgore College. They placed 1st in the group routine (I Like It), 2nd Flag Line (Ain’t Nothing), and 3rd Twirlers (We’re Not Gonna Take It). They also received Outstanding Costume for whole competition, Flag/Baton Handling Excellence for Ain’t Nothing and Flag Line Outstanding Presentation for Ain’t Nothing.
